full_text: ProducerCode security restricts user access to accounts, policies and jobs. Producers with different ProducerCodes cannot view each other's book of business. After logging in as SuperUser, in the organization Armstrong and Company, check the ProducerCodes and which users have them. Click the ProducerCode for Armstrong, Los Angeles. Go to the Users tab. Note the list of users for ProducerCode 500120252. The user PaytonArmstrong is in the list, while Eli Armstrong is not in the list. Log out SuperUser. Log in as PaytonArmstrong. Create a new account and submission. Click Account. Select New Account. Select New Account. Create an account for Floral Shop. Enter the Company Name. Click Search. It returns 0 result. Click Create New Account. Select Company. Enter the New Account information. Open the ProducerCode drop-down. Select the Code for Armstrong, Los Angeles. Save the Account Info. Note down the Account Number. Next, click the Actions Menu. Select New Submission. Select the Business Owner's Product. Note the Submission Number. Log out PaytonArmstrong. Click OK to confirm. Log in as Eli Armstrong. Click Account. Log out to the Account. In the Account Number Quick Search field, type in the Account Number for the account that was just created, and search for it. Filogy of  An informational message is displayed that the search returns zero results. Next click the Policy menu. In the Submission Number Quick Search field, type in the submission number. Click the search icon. Policy Center displays a similar error that the Eli cannot access the policy. Log out Eli Armstrong. Who can view these accounts and submission other than Peyton Armstrong? Log in as a user who has the same producer code as that on the account or submission. For example, Archie Armstrong. Click the Account menu. In the Account Number field, type in the same account number, and search for it. The user is able to view the account and the submission successfully. This is the end of demonstration for producer code security.
